{{ill|Nichu Shrine|ja|日雲神社|qq=draft}} is a {{ill|Moto-Ise Shrines|lt=Motoise shrine|ja|元伊勢|1=Moto-Ise Shrines|qq=draft}}.

Moto-Ise Shrines are {{ill|Shinto shrines|ja|神社|qq=draft}} that used to host Amaterasu before she was moved to {{ill|Ise Jingu|ja|伊勢神宮|qq=draft}}. The first one was {{ill|Hibara Shrine|ja|檜原神社|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Ōmiwa Shrine|ja|大神神社|qq=draft}}).

*
==Overview==
{{神社
|名称=日雲神社
|image=[[File:Hikumo-jinja.JPG|250px]]<br />日雲神社　拝殿
|所在地={{ill|Shiga Prefecture|ja|滋賀県|qq=draft}}{{ill|Koka City|ja|甲賀市|qq=draft}} 信楽町牧75
|位置={{ウィキ座標2段度分秒|34|54|28.4|N|136|05|00.1|E|region:JP-25_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}
|祭神={{ill|Ame-no-Minakanushi|ja|天御中主神|qq=draft}}
|社格={{ill|village shrine|ja|村社|lt=former village shrine|lt_ja=旧村社|qq=draft}}
|創建=Founding date unknown
|本殿=Three-bay shrine {{ill|Nagare-zukuri|ja|流造|qq=draft}}
|例祭={{ill|May 5|ja|5月5日|qq=draft}}
|神事=Taiko Dance
}}
'''Nichu Shrine''' (日雲神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft}} located at 75 Makimachi, Shigaraki, {{ill|Koka City|ja|甲賀市|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Shiga Prefecture|ja|滋賀県|qq=draft}}.

== {{nihongo|Worshipped Deities|祭神|Saijin}} ==
* {{ill|Ame-no-Minakanushi|ja|天御中主神|qq=draft}}

== Shrine Emblem ==
* Ume Bowl (梅鉢)

== History ==
Although its founding date is unknown, the origin is traditionally attributed to the {{ill|Moto-Ise Shrines|ja|元伊勢|1=Moto-Ise Shrines|qq=draft}} "'''Koka-Hikumo Shrine''' (甲可日雲宮)" recorded in {{ill|Shinto Gobu-sho|ja|神道五部書|lt=Ise Shinto Gobu-sho|lt_ja=伊勢神道五部書|qq=draft}} and the chronicle {{ill|Yamato Hime no Mikoto Chronicles|ja|倭姫命世記|qq=draft}}. The main hall is said to have been constructed in {{ill|Genroku|ja|元禄|qq=draft}} 4 (1691). It was once known as "Uenoyama Tenjin" and "Makimura Tenmangu", but in {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft}} 18 (1885) its name was changed to the current one. The precincts are traversed by the {{ill|Shigaraki Kogen Railway|ja|信楽高原鐵道|qq=draft}}. In {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft}} 9 (1876) it was listed as a {{ill|village shrine|ja|村社|qq=draft}}.

== Festivals ==
* Annual Festival: May 5

== Cultural Properties ==
* Main Hall – A three-bay shrine structure in the {{ill|Nagare-zukuri|ja|流造|qq=draft}} style with a cypress bark roof {{ill|Cypress bark roof|ja|檜皮葺|qq=draft}}, said to have been constructed in {{ill|Genroku|ja|元禄|qq=draft}} 4 (1691). It is registered as a National {{ill|Registered tangible cultural property|ja|登録有形文化財|qq=draft}} as a representative example of the Nagare-zukuri tradition in Ōmi since the medieval period.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Koka City History Vol.8 Koka City Encyclopedia|date=2016-12-12|year=2016|publisher=Koka City}}</ref>
* Hexagonal Stone Lantern – Possessing an inscription from the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kagen|ja|嘉元|qq=draft}} 4 (1306), designated as a cultural property by Koka City.
* Taiko Dance – Selected intangible {{ill|Folk Cultural Property|ja|民俗文化財|qq=draft}} of Shiga Prefecture.

== Shrine Auxiliary Facilities ==
* On-site Shrines
** {{ill|Hachiman Shrine|ja|八幡神社|qq=draft}}
